<DocsLayout title="High Availability">
  <h1>High Availability</h1>
  <p>
    EncodeSwarmr supports active-passive high availability for production deployments that require fault tolerance.
  </p>

  <h2>Controller HA</h2>
  <p>
    Controller HA uses PostgreSQL advisory locks to ensure only one instance is actively processing jobs at any time. The setup:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>Deploy two or more Controller instances pointing to the same PostgreSQL database</li>
    <li>One instance acquires the advisory lock and becomes the <strong>active</strong> leader</li>
    <li>Other instances remain in <strong>standby</strong>, serving only read-only API requests</li>
    <li>If the active instance fails, a standby acquires the lock and becomes active</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Configuration</h3>
  <pre><code>ha:
  enabled: true
  lock_refresh_interval: 5s   # How often to refresh the advisory lock
  lock_timeout: 30s           # How long before a stale lock is considered expired</code></pre>

  <h2>Database HA</h2>
  <p>
    For database-level high availability, EncodeSwarmr recommends Patroni with pgBouncer:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Patroni</strong> — Manages PostgreSQL replication and automatic failover</li>
    <li><strong>pgBouncer</strong> — Connection pooling to handle failover transparently</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Point the Controller's database configuration at the pgBouncer endpoint. Patroni handles failover automatically.</p>

  <h2>Load Balancing</h2>
  <p>
    Place a load balancer (nginx, HAProxy, or cloud LB) in front of Controller instances:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>HTTP traffic</strong> (port 8080) — Round-robin or least-connections to any instance</li>
    <li><strong>gRPC traffic</strong> (port 9443) — Route to the active instance only</li>
    <li>Use the <code>/health</code> endpoint for health checks</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Health Check Response</h3>
  <pre><code>GET /health

# Active instance:
&#123;"status": "ok", "role": "active", "version": "1.0.0"&#125;

# Standby instance:
&#123;"status": "ok", "role": "standby", "version": "1.0.0"&#125;</code></pre>

  <h2>Agent Resilience</h2>
  <p>
    Agents are inherently resilient to Controller failover:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>gRPC connections automatically reconnect with exponential backoff</li>
    <li>In-progress jobs continue during failover</li>
    <li>Results buffer in the local SQLite journal until connectivity is restored</li>
    <li>No manual intervention required on the agent side</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Deployment Architecture</h2>
  <pre><code>                    Load Balancer
                    ┌──────────┐
                    │ nginx/LB │
                    └────┬─────┘
                ┌────────┼────────┐
          ┌─────┴─────┐     ┌────┴──────┐
          │Controller 1│     │Controller 2│
          │  (active)  │     │ (standby)  │
          └─────┬──────┘     └─────┬──────┘
                └────────┬─────────┘
              ┌──────────┴──────────┐
              │ PostgreSQL (Patroni) │
              │   Primary + Replica  │
              └──────────────────────┘</code></pre>

